title: Rifle inventory records (Orange County Sheriff's Office)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Rifle inventory records (Orange County Sheriff's Office)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. Records of the most recent inventory of rifles possessed by the Sheriff's Office, as defined in Sections 30510 and 30515 of the Penal Code (assault rifles, patrol rifles, sniper rifles, .50 caliber rifles).
2. Records indicating the number of rifles, as defined in Sections 30510 and 30515 of the Penal Code,  privately possessed by personnel of the Sheriff's Office with its authorization, OR the number of Sheriff's Office personnel with such authorization.

To assist with the prompt release of responsive material, I ask that you make records available to me as you locate them, rather than waiting until all responsive records have been collected and copied.
 
The requested documents or information from them will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

If you would like to discuss these requests, please feel free to reach out to me, John Lindsay-Poland, co-director of the American Friends Service Committee California Healing Justice Program at jlindsay-poland@afsc.org or by phone at 510-282-8983.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

John Lindsay-Poland

communications.subject: Anonymous -  - UW-Madison Public Records Request - P2025-229
communications.communication:
RE: Records Request: Request Number: P2025-229 - Submitted On: 7/3/2025 
  
 Dear Requestor, 
  
 This message is regarding: Request Number: P2025-229 
  
 I would like a spreadsheet containing all the academic dishonesty reports from the beginning of the Fall 2021 semester to the end of the Spring 2025 Semester, organized by university college. 
  
 I have begun reviewing records in this request. I received the initial data in excel but have discovered after review has begun that Fried B contains student identifiable information that must be redacted. This data is scattered intermittently in the field and is much more efficiently redacted in adobe. Therefore I have converted the records to adobe for redaction. 
  
 Field A however is the class title, which appears to be more what you are looking for. We do not keep these records by university college as you have requested. They will not be provided that way. 
  
 I have two alternatives for you: 
  
 Alt 1: Get in excel Field A (only) which is the "count" and class abbreviation for each count of academic dishonesty reported to the Dean of Students office. 
  
 Alt 2: Get Fields A and B in adobe so they can be redacted in accordance with the requirements of federal law. We simply do not have the staff capital to redact in excel which takes at least twice as long as redaction in adobe when we currently have 120 other requesters waiting for records. 
  
 Please reply by 8.28.25 with you alternative choice. Obviously Alt 1 will be a quick turnaround after that, Alt will take longer. 
  
 Of you do not reply by August 28th, I will take silence as acceptance of Alt 1 and will reply with that material. You may always make a new request. 
  
 Thank you, 
  
 Julie Laundrie 
 Public Records Custodian 
 Office of Compliance 
 University of Wisconsin-Madison 
  
 University of Wisconsin-Madison 
 500 Lincoln Drive
361 Bascom Hall
Madison, Wisconsin 53706 
 (608) 265-6018

communications.subject: RE: Wisconsin Open Records Act Request #P2025-229
communications.communication:
To whom it may concern,

Thank you for responding to our request. I should have been more specific in the initial request. In the request, the total number of academic dishonesty reports for each of the following years:

2021-22
2022-23
2023-24
2024-25

We do not need any student names, faculty names, department names, or college names, only the total number of dishonesty reports for each year. With that qualifier, I believe this would no longer fall under FERPA protection, since no record is tied to an individual and all records are aggregated to the college level. Thank you in advance for your cooperation

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Johann "Jack" Unterweger FBI File
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

FBI files pertaining to Johann "Jack" Unterweger (16 August 1950  – 29 June 1994), who was an Austrian serial killer who committed at least twelve murders in Austria, West Germany, Czechoslovakia and the United States. Unterweger was under FBI surveillance circa 1992, when he fled Austria to Miami, where he was arrested on Feb 27, 1992.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Unterweger

Please search first for any prior releases and/or pre-processed files, and release them on a rolling basis before processing any new material generated by this request. 

If no prior releases are available, please kindly conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, however as noted below, please inform me prior to performing any searches incurring fees.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Elizabeth J Klein

title: Organized Retail Crime Task Force: Auror

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Organized Retail Crime Task Force: Auror
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to the Organized Retail Crime Theft Task Force announced on June 23, 2022, specifically concerning the implementation, use, and discussion of Auror's crime intelligence platform.

1. All contracts, MOUs, RFPs, or service agreements between the AG's Office and Auror Inc. (auror.co) dated June 23, 2022, to present
1a. Amendments, scope-of-work documents, or SLA agreements related to Auror's services
1b. Invoices, payment receipts, or procurement documents for Auror software/services

2. Budget allocations specific to Auror platform implementation
2a. Documentation of federal/state grants used to fund Auror-related expenditures

3. Training manuals, guides, or protocols for Auror platform use by task force members
3a. Video recordings of Auror software training sessions
3b. Email communications regarding training schedules or materials

4. All incident reports, intelligence briefings, or case files generated through Auror's platform
4a. Spreadsheets/databases tracking organized retail crime incidents processed via Auror
4b. Performance metrics/reports evaluating Auror's effectiveness (2022-2024)

5. Records of technical malfunctions, data inaccuracies, or security breaches involving Auror
5a. Formal complaints from task force members or partner agencies about Auror's system
5b. Internal audits or third-party assessments of Auror's compliance with state data laws

6. Emails/memos between AG staff and Auror representatives (June 23, 2022-present)
6a. Meeting minutes where Auror platform use was discussed
6b. Correspondence with federal partners (FBI, DHS) regarding Auror data sharing

These records are requested from June 23, 2022, to present; Electronic copies are preferred in their original formats wherever possible, and commonly readable formats such as pdf, mp4, png where conversion is required.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robin Monks

communications.subject: FOIA Request 25-02951-F 20 Day Status Notification
communications.communication:
April 23, 2025 Adam Steinbaugh 
MuckRock News 
DEPT MR 182717 
263 Huntington Ave 
Boston, MA  02115 RE: FOIA Request No. 25-02951-F Dear Adam Steinbaugh: This is a status update regarding your request for information pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA), 5 U.S.C. § 552, dated March 18, 2025, and received in the U.S. Department of Education’s (Department) FOIA Service Center (FSC) on March 19, 2025. When received, your request was forwarded to the appropriate office(s) within the Department to conduct a search for any responsive records. At this time, your request is still being processed. 
We appreciate your patience as we work diligently to process your request. Please be advised that the average request processing time is approximately 185 business days. As this is an average, your request may take more time or may be processed sooner. You can check the status of your request at https://foiaxpress.pal.ed.gov/app/CheckStatus.aspx 
Narrowing or reformulating a request can often lead to decreased processing times. If you are interested in reformulating or narrowing your request, or have any other questions, please contact the FSC at 202-401-8365 or EDFOIAManager@ed.gov. You have the right to seek assistance and/or dispute resolution services from the Department’s FOIA Public Liaison or the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS). The FOIA Public Liaison is responsible, among other duties, for assisting in the resolution of FOIA disputes. The FOIA Public Liaison may also assist in reformulating or narrowing your request. OGIS, which is outside the Department, offers ombuds services, including dispute resolution, to assist FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation. You may contact the FOIA Public Liaison or OGIS at: FOIA Public Liaison Office of the Deputy Secretary U.S. Department of Education 400 Maryland Ave., SW, LBJ 7W104 Washington, DC 20202-4500 Email: robert.wehausen@ed.gov Phone: 202-205-0733 Fax: 202-401-0920 Office of Government Information Services National Archives and Records Administration 8601 Adelphi Road, OGIS College Park, MD 20740-6001 Email: OGIS@nara.gov Phone: 202-741-5770 or 1-877-684-6448 Sincerely, ED FOIA Service Center Office of the Deputy Secretary

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

RE: Public Records Request, Reference # H026526-121724 Dear Mrs. Samantha Liss, 

This notice is issued in response to your request, legally received by the Michigan Department of Health and Human Services (Department) on December 18, 2024, requesting information under the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA), MCL 15.231 et seq. 

Your request is granted as to existing nonexempt records. 

The Department has determined the cost for searching, retrieval, and review of the requested records and separation of exempt and nonexempt information. The cost of your FOIA request is stated in the invoice located in the MDHHS Public Records Center, where you may pay your invoice online. Bureau of Legal Affairs

communications.subject: Maryland Public Information Act Request: Police Foundations PR (Baltimore Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Maryland Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Hello, 

I am seeking records as they relate to the department and donations, grants, or other gifts from police nonprofits, including Foundations, Benevolent Funds, Boosters, Activities Leagues, and Associations. Include local and national police nonprofits.

Documents, physical or digital copies of: 
Memorandum of Understanding or any formal agreements with nonprofits.
Polices related to accepting and soliciting donations, monetary and nonmonetary, and grants from any nonprofit.
Policies or requirements by the department on how donations are to be tracked.
Policies regarding any conflict of interest requirements.
Formal grant requests or donation requests filled out by the department or a representative for the department.

Databases that include spreadsheets or whatever form the department tracks such information: 
Donor name
What was donated, monetary and non-monetary value
Date
Release data in .csv form 

For grant and donation data, please only include items and cash valued $500 or more.
Limit searches to 2020 to 2025

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joey Scott

On August 1, 2025, you submitted a request for public records to the Document Compliance Unit ("DCU") of the Baltimore Police Department ("BPD"), for records as they relate to the department and donations, grants, or other gifts from police nonprofits, including Foundations, Benevolent Funds, Boosters, Activities Leagues, and Associations. Include local and national police nonprofits.

Documents, physical or digital copies of:
Memorandum of Understanding or any formal agreements with nonprofits.
Polices related to accepting and soliciting donations, monetary and nonmonetary, and grants from any nonprofit.
Policies or requirements by the department on how donations are to be tracked.
Policies regarding any conflict of interest requirements.
Formal grant requests or donation requests filled out by the department or a representative for the department.

Databases that include spreadsheets or whatever form the department tracks such information:
Donor name
What was donated, monetary and non-monetary value
Date
Release data in .csv form

Limit searches to 2020 to 2025."

DCU Response:

Attached are the full year reports for fiscal years 2020, 2021, 2022, and 2023 on the expenditure of grants that the Baltimore Police Department received from the Governor's Office of Crime Control and Prevention.

Nothing in this response is intended to indicate that any records sought from BPD exist or to waive any privileges held by BPD. You have a right under the Public Information Act for the Public Access Ombudsman to mediate any disputes arising out of a MPIA request or a judicial review pursuant to General Provisions Article §§ 4-1B-04, 4-362. Please refer to Tracking Number # MPIA 25-3469 in any subsequent correspondence in this matter.

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Rifle inventory records (Office of the Sheriff - Contra Costa County)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. Records of the most recent inventory of rifles possessed by the Sheriff's Office, as defined in Sections 30510 and 30515 of the Penal Code (assault rifles, patrol rifles, sniper rifles, .50 caliber rifles).
2. Records indicating the number of rifles, as defined in Sections 30510 and 30515 of the Penal Code,  privately possessed by personnel of the Sheriff's Office with its authorization, OR the number of Sheriff's Office personnel with such authorization.

To assist with the prompt release of responsive material, I ask that you make records available to me as you locate them, rather than waiting until all responsive records have been collected and copied.
 
The requested documents or information from them will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

If you would like to discuss these requests, please feel free to reach out to me, John Lindsay-Poland, co-director of the American Friends Service Committee California Healing Justice Program at jlindsay-poland@afsc.org or by phone at 510-282-8983.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

John Lindsay-Poland

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #60849
communications.communication:
Hi Aspen,

I think you misunderstood my reference to WAPA letters.  They are not the criminal investigations.  They are the letter you had previously stated you did not want in your email dated July 30, 2025, as referenced below:

“Another county got my request confused and sent letters they received from WAPA that relate to WSP officers on the Brady list”

It may help to understand that Island County is comprised of multiple “agencies” for the purposes of the Public Records Act.  This is because county government is an amalgam of independently elected officials who maintain exclusive control over their areas of authority, with respect to other county officials.  I maintain exclusive control over the records that pertain to the operation of the Prosecuting Attorney’s Office.   The complete misconduct record will be housed with the originating law enforcement agency.

For the four individuals listed for the Island County Sheriff’s Office below:

  *   Gardner, Teri – her potential impeachment issue was while employed with Oak Harbor Police Department.  They will have her full investigation.  We have legal memorandums, which are attached with this email.
  *   Wallace, Jay – this is still in pending status and we have no documentation.
  *   Wrightson, James P. – this is still in pending status and we have no documentation.
  *   Nieder, John – Mr. Neider was arrested in Skagit county on rape charges.  We do not have Skagit County Sheriff’s Office investigation for this criminal charge.  We have the court charging document, Motion for Probable Cause and Order on First Appearance regarding first arraignment hearing date and bail amount.  These are all court documents and not the investigation.  They are attached with this email for your reference.

I’ve included the records we do have for Mr. Nieder and Ms. Gardner as well as a redaction log exempting Mr. Nieder’s driver’s license number.  Your closure date for your request will still be August 14, 2025,  for your one-year date to seek judicial review of this request.

If you have any further questions, please let me know.

With kind regards,

Lynn Brennan
Civil Paralegal/Public Records Officer
Island County Prosecuting Attorney

Coupeville, Washington 98239

communications.subject: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: Admissions Data Follow-up
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Virginia Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

As you requested in your last message, this is a follow-up for additional clarifying data to that released under FOIA 27-77.

While providing the reasons for requesting the records and their use is not required under the FOIA, we wanted to do that as a courtesy as it may save the level of effort on your part to know that as well as identify what we “should have asked for” but didn’t. The other schools we’re contacting for data to use in the trends analysis found that helpful as when we get the data from multiple sources it needs to end up being “apples to apples”.

Pursuant to the Virginia Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

The overall purpose of the project is to do a comparative analysis of admissions for Peer or near-peer colleges and university to identify trends that may impact planning and execution of admissions strategies and goals. To that end we need not only the student demographics, but the application and admissions timelines.

For example. If the majority of applicants do not make their decision on completing the application or accepting the offer to attend until shortly before a matriculation date that creates a serious planning issue for Institutions like VMI who have to plan for a wide range and do not have sufficient reaction time to implement mitigations strategies. This would be of benefit to many colleges as we do not believe such analysis is ongoing.

In VMI’s case there was one year where it appears due to COVID and other factors enrollment (those who matriculated) was extremely low. If the perspective students did not notify VMI until shortly before (or just did not show up) it puts the school in a bind to provide opportunities to others and, more importantly, may have left some good potential students without sufficient time to react and arrive to matriculate.

It is one goal to see what the trend is for today’s freshmen on when they make the decisions and what visibility schools have of that.

Academic years covered:

2015 - 2016
2016 - 2017
2017 - 2018
2018 - 2019
2019 - 2020
2020 - 2021
2021 - 2022
2022 - 2023
2023 - 2024
2024 - 2025

REQUEST 1: An excel or .CSV file of the entire SSR database (report) as provided in the last FOIA with all fields, except for PII and an explanation of the field codes.

This would be the best as it would require little to no level of effort on VMI’s part to simply export the entire file(s) without any PII fields. 

We respectfully request this as it may have some fields we do not know exist in the report/database that could be valuable in our research.

ALETRNATE: If it is not possible to just provide files of the entire database (minus PII) we request the following.

1.	A list of all SSR codes and their meaning for all fields in the SSR Database.

2.	The breakout of ALL applicants to VMI by race, ethnicity, gender, and within each of those, which were athletes and non-athletes:

a.	Date of initial contact
b.	Date of Initial Application
c.	Date of full application competition
d.	Date Accepted or Declined by VMI (i.e. Appointment or denied appointment)
e.	Date of partial deposit
f.	Date of full deposit
g.	Date CAD- cancelled after paying the deposit (but before becoming a full reservation)
h.	Date CBD- cancelled before paying the deposit
i.	Date CR- cancelled after becoming a full reservation (deposit paid and medicals approved)
j.	Date TDMD- appointed but medically disqualified
k.	Date MT- matriculated
l.	Other fields that will allow developing trends and profiles of the timeline between cadets applying to VMI and final disposition if they attend or not.

3. The number and dollar value of each scholarship or tuition assistance for each MT cadet by race, ethnicity, gender, and within each of those, which were athletes and non-athletes, with the source of funding (e.g., VMI Agencies, Federal Government, VMI internal funds, other).

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tom Nash, a citizen of Virginia, in coordination with Anonymous.

Dear FOIA Officer,

Unfortunately, once again, the records I requested and paid for are incomplete.

This is an addendum to my prior Virginia Freedom of Information Act request regarding Virginia Military Institute (VMI) admissions records for the 2019–2028 period.

Upon review of the records provided, I request the following additional fields specifically for the 2028 admissions cycle:

Application Start Date (InDate): the date each applicant to the Class of 2028 began their application.

Application Completion Date (CmpDate): the date each applicant to the Class of 2028 completed their application file.

These fields are present in the datasets for prior years (2019–2027) but were absent from the 2028 dataset provided. 

As previously requested, please provide these records in electronic format (CSV, Excel, or equivalent). 

Thank you for your continued assistance. Please confirm receipt of this addendum and provide an estimated timeline for fulfillment.

As soon as I am in receipt of the records I requested, I will pay for this FOIA.

communications.subject: [External Message Added] Virginia Military Institute public records request #25-109
communications.communication:
Virginia Military Institute ************************************************************************ A message was sent to you regarding record request #25-109: A couple of points of clarification: 1.) You have not paid for this request; and 2.) Since this has come up in several of your responses, you are not paying for records. Rather, you are paying for the cost of VMI to fulfill your requests. It is entirely possible that a requester pays for a request to be fulfilled, and they do not receive any responsive records because the records are exempt from disclosure or do not exist. Please keep in mind you are paying for the time that VMI employees are taken away from our mission of training and educating citizen-soldiers. With respect to the responsive records provided, the InDate and CmpDate are not included in the SSR report for the Class of 2028 and beyond. That data is not imported from the CommonApp into VMI’s student information system and is, therefore, not available in the 2028 and future reports. To add it to the dataset would constitute the creation of a new record which VMI is under no obligation to do (Va. Code § 2.2-3704.D.). ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? communications.subject: RE: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request ##25-109
communications.communication:
I understand that  completely and wish to avoid the semantics of "paying for records" versus "paying for the time to collect the records." In the end, the cost paid is to "obtain the records" regardless of what that funding goes to.  It's irrelevant to the issue at hand.

In this case, the situation is simple. ALL of the records provided, apparently from the SAME database, from 2019 - 2027 have the same fields.  With the the 2028 date, apparently from the same database,  the following two fields were NOT in the exported spreadsheet:

1. Field "InDate" - Application Start Date (InDate): the date each applicant to the Class of 2028 began their application.

2. Field "CmpDate" - Application Completion Date (CmpDate): the date each applicant to the Class of 2028 completed their application file.

I brought that to your attention in the context that it likely resulted from an error in exporting the file, which did not include those fields in the Excel file, and I asked you to correct it.  I should not reasonably be expected to pay for additional "time" to fix this. Seems to me a simple matter.

HOWEVER, your response raises some straightforward questions.

1. If those fields NO LONGER exist in the database after 2027, then VMI is NO LONGER TRACKING the Date a potential Cadet Starts and application, and the Date a potential Cadet completes an application, thereby changing your way of doing business for the previous EIGHT YEARS. In this case, a "no responsive records, VMI no longer collects the Application start and completion dates" would suffice.

2. If you do still collect that data, it was requested in the FOIA, and you did not provide it in that second file, so I am simply asking that it be corrected.

Regarding the other requests, your responses to my inquiry about missing records are incomplete at best.  If a requester requests records, any normally operating FOIA office returns a response with the requested records (and, in some cases, the "work" paid for), then annotates the request with a simple explanation stating that "Record XXX does not exist."  

This eliminates the perception (as there clearly is here) that the agency is only selectively releasing records.

In conclusion, all I reasonably expect from this FOIA is that VMI either say you no longer track those two important data fields or simply fix what I originally considered a simple processing error (but now have my doubts).

Thank you for your prompt response.

Once you either provide the data I am charged for or explain why it does not exist anymore at VMI I will pay you for your "time".

communications.subject: [External Message Added] Virginia Military Institute public records request #25-109

Virginia Military Institute ************************************************************************ A message was sent to you regarding record request #25-109: As the previous message clearly stated, the missing fields are not "an error in the exporting file," but rather a result from the change in application processes and the data that is collected after that change. The previous response clearly stated those fields were no longer part of the 2028 report requested. The Admissions staff has been contacted to see if they can extract that data from the database maintained by the CommonApp. VMI is under no obligation to do so according to Virginia law. However, in the spirit of transparency, they agreed to take time away from their responsibilities of recruiting future cadets to look into it. If they are able to access the data, you will be notified and it will be added to the folder of responsive records. If not, you will also be notified. ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? Reply to this email or sign in to contact staff at Virginia Military Institute.

RESPONSE: Documents responsive to your request are available to download via the CPS FOIA Center at www.cps.edu/FOIARequests . Please log in with your username and password to access the records. Please note that certain private information (personal descriptions, employee ID numbers, college transcripts, social security numbers, citizenship status, signatures, personal addresses/phone numbers, medical information, etc.) was redacted pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7. Specifically, section 7(1)(b) which exempts certain private information as defined by section 2(c-5) and section 7(1)(c) which exempts personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy, unless the disclosure is consented to in writing by the individual subject of the information. “Unwarranted invasion of personal privacy” means the disclosure of information that is highly personal or objectionable to a reasonable person and in which the subject’s right to privacy outweighs any legitimate public interest in obtaining the information. 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(a) exempts “ information specifically prohibited from disclosure by federal or State Law … ” (5 ILCS 140/7(1)(a)) Specifically, 105 ILCS 5/10-21.9 (b) states that “ any information concerning the record of convictions obtained by the president of the school board or the regional superintendent shall be confidential and may only be transmitted to the superintendent of the school district or his designee, the appropriate regional superintendent if the check was requested by the school district, the presidents of the appropriate school boards if the check was requested from the Department of State Police by the regional superintendent, the State Superintendent of Education, the State Teacher Certification Board, any other person necessary to the decision of hiring the applicant for employment, or for clarification purposes the Department of State Police or Statewide Sex Offender Database, or both.” 
Portions of this request that include personnel evaluations are redacted entirely in accordance with section 7(1)(a) of FOIA (5 ILCS 140/7(1)(a)) which exempts from public release information specifically prohibited from disclosure by federal or State law or rules and regulations implementing federal or State law and also in accordance with section 7.5(q) of the FOIA (5 ILCS 140/7.5(q)) which exempts from public release information prohibited from being disclosed by the Personnel Records Review Act [820 ILCS 40/0.01 et seq.] Docusign ID Codes were redacted pursuant to (5 ILCS 140/ 7(1)(u), which exempts information that would disclose or might lead to the disclosure of secret or confidential information, codes, algorithms, programs, or private keys intended to be used to create electronic or digital signatures under the Electronic Commerce Security Act Student/parent information has been redacted pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7.5 (r) which exempts from inspection or copying information prohibited from being disclosed by the Illinois School Student Records Act (ISSRA). ISSRA generally prohibits the disclosure of “school student records” and defines a “school student record” as “any writing or other recorded information concerning a student and by which a student may be individually identified, maintained by a school or at is direction or by an employee of a school, regardless of how or where the information is stored.” (105 ILCS 10/2(d). The identity of a complainant has been redacted pursuant to section 7(d)(iv) of the FOIA which exempts confidential information furnished only by the confidential source, or persons who file complaints with or provide information to administrative, investigative, law enforcement, or penal agencies. Certain records are being withheld entirely pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(f) as factual information inextricably intertwined in ongoing investigation and processes as well as 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(n), which exempts from release records relating to the adjudication of employee discipline and grievance matters except for records reflecting the final outcome. You have a right to have the denial of your request reviewed by the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at the Office of the Illinois Attorney General. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). You can file your Request for Review with the PAC by writing to: Leah Bartelt; Public Access Counselor Office of the Attorney General 500 South 2nd Street Springfield, Illinois 62706 E-mail: public.access@ilag.gov 877-299-3642 You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court. 5 ILCS 140/11. If you choose to file a Request for Review with the PAC, you must do so within 60 calendar days of the date of this denial letter. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). Please note that you must include a copy of your original FOIA request and this denial letter when filing a Request for Review with the PAC. Sincerely, Patricia Majchrowicz Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

Under the West Virginia Freedom of Information Act, §29-B-1-1 et seq., I am requesting an opportunity to inspect or obtain copies of public records that show the following; the total opioid settlement funds received by Logan County, the application that individuals or organizations seeking funding from the county complete, copies of grant applications from individuals or organizations that have been approved to receive these funds, the names of individuals who will review the funding applications, any meeting minutes of county-level officials where the receiving or distribution of county-level opioid settlement funding was discussed, and how much funding has been awarded as of March 1, 2025, and to whom it was awarded.
If there are any fees for searching or copying these records, please inform me if the cost will exceed $25. However, I would also like to request a waiver of all fees in that the disclosure of the requested information is in the public interest and will contribute significantly to the public’s understanding of how this large sum of allocated funds is being distributed across the county.
 I am a student reporter at West Virginia University and intend to use this information to more accurately report on these findings. This information is not being sought for commercial purposes. 
The West Virginia Freedom of Information Act requires a response to this request be made within five business days. If access to the records I am requesting will take longer than this amount of time, please contact me with information about when I might expect copies or the ability to inspect the requested records. You can call me at 304-550-3523 or send me an email at tpm00003@mix.wvu.edu My physical address is 234 Domain Drive, Apartment 234, Morgantown, WV 26501. 
If you deny any or all of this request, please cite each specific exemption you feel justifies the refusal to release the information and notify me of the appeal procedures available to me under the law. 
Thank you for considering my request. 
Sincerely, 
Ty McClung 
304-550-3523
tpm00003@mix.wvu.edu

title: Third Party Investigative Platform (Purchase and Contract records) (Fayetteville Police Department)

communications.subject: North Carolina Public Records Law Request: Third Party Investigative Platform (Purchase and Contract records) (Fayetteville Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the North Carolina Public Records Law, I hereby request the records listed below regarding the following four software programs: 

• Thompson Reuters Clear (https://legal.thomsonreuters.com/en/products/clear)
• LexisNexis Accurint (https://www.accurint.com/)
• TransUnion TLOxp, which may also be part of the TruLookup system (https://www.tlo.com/law-enforcement)
• SoundThinking CrimeTracer, which was formerly a product called COPLINK X (https://www.soundthinking.com/law-enforcement/crime-analysis-crimetracer/) from the company formerly known as ShotSpotter

For each of the above mentioned platforms, please provide the following records: 

• CONTRACTS AND AGREEMENTS —  All contracts (as well as associated amendments, attachments, and exhibits) and agreements related to the acquisition and use of these "software" programs.
• PURCHASE INFORMATION — All invoices and purchase information for costs and products associated with the above-referenced platforms.

Please provide responsive materials for the period from January 1, 2021 through the date this request is processed. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Alin Beane

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Raphael Sanchez and Jonathan Love e-mails
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. All e-mail messages between former ICE Trial Attorney Jonathan M. Love and former ICE Attorney Raphael Sanchez from January 1, 2015 to February 19, 2018, including e-mail messages from Sanchez to Love, from Love to Sanchez, from Love to a third party where Sanchez is copied as a "carbon copy" or "blind carbon copy," and Sanchez to a third party where Love is copied as a "carbon copy" or "blind carbon copy." 

2. Any e-mail messages from the ICE e-mail address for Jonathan M. Love in which the following e-mail address is the recipient, either directly or by "carbon copy" or "blind carbon copy": "Raphael_Sanchez@yahoo.com"

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Matthew Hoppock

Your request was received in this office on 5/24/2023.Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request. Per Section 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, 6 C.F.R. Part 5, ICE processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt. Although ICE’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, the FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period. As your request seeks numerous documents that will necessitate a thorough and wide-ranging search, ICE will invoke a 10-day extension for your request, as allowed by Title 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B). If you’re able to narrow the scope of your request please contact our office. Narrowing the scope may speed up the search process. We will make every effort to comply with your request in a timely manner. Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations as they apply to non-commercial requesters.  As a non-commercial requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free, as are the first two hours of search time, after which you will pay the per quarter-hour rate ($4.00 for clerical personnel, $7.00 for professional personnel, $10.25 for managerial personnel) of the searcher.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued.We have queried the appropriate program offices within ICE for responsive records. If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability. title: Public Records Request — Courtney Clenney / Christian Obumseli Homicide (Miami-Dade County Police)

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Public Records Request — Courtney Clenney / Christian Obumseli Homicide (Miami-Dade County Police)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

Pursuant to Florida’s Public Records Law (Chapter 119, Florida Statutes), I request access to the following records relating to the homicide of Christian Obumseli by Courtney Clenney on April 3, 2022, at the One Paraiso Apartments, Miami, Florida:

- All body-worn camera footage from responding officers.
- Any dashcam or in-car camera recordings.
- All 911 call recordings associated with this incident.
- CAD dispatch logs and radio communications.
- Any interview room or interrogation recordings (audio/video) of Courtney Clenney or witnesses.
- Complete incident and investigative reports, including supplemental reports.
- Any crime scene evidence photos or videos generated in this case.

If any portion of these records is exempt from disclosure, please release all reasonably segregable portions and provide statutory justification for redactions or denials.

This request is made for journalistic/documentary purposes and is in the public interest.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

James Shaw

Thank you for your interest in public records of Miami-Dade Sheriff's Office.  Your request has been received and is being processed.  Your request was received in this office on 9/1/2025 and given the reference number P333621-090125 for tracking purposes.  To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

Pursuant to Florida’s Public Records Law (Chapter 119, Florida Statutes), I request access to the following records relating to the homicide of Christian Obumseli by Courtney Clenney on April 3, 2022, at the One Paraiso Apartments, Miami, Florida:

- All body-worn camera footage from responding officers.
- Any dashcam or in-car camera recordings.
- All 911 call recordings associated with this incident.
- CAD dispatch logs and radio communications.
- Any interview room or interrogation recordings (audio/video) of Courtney Clenney or witnesses.
- Complete incident and investigative reports, including supplemental reports.
- Any crime scene evidence photos or videos generated in this case.

If any portion of these records is exempt from disclosure, please release all reasonably segregable portions and provide statutory justification for redactions or denials.

This request is made for journalistic/documentary purposes and is in the public interest.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

James Shaw

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Police Foundations PR (San Diego Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Hello, 

I am seeking records as they relate to the department and donations, grants, or other gifts from police nonprofits, including Foundations, Benevolent Funds, Boosters, Activities Leagues, and Associations. Include local and national police nonprofits.

Documents, physical or digital copies of: 
Memorandum of Understanding or any formal agreements with nonprofits.
Polices related to accepting and soliciting donations, monetary and nonmonetary, and grants from any nonprofit.
Policies or requirements by the department on how donations are to be tracked.
Policies regarding any conflict of interest requirements.
Formal grant requests or donation requests filled out by the department or a representative for the department.

Databases that include spreadsheets or whatever form the department tracks such information: 
Donor name
What was donated, monetary and non-monetary value
Date
Release data in .csv form 

For grant and donation data, please only include items and cash valued $500 or more.
Limit searches to 2020 to 2025

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Joey Scott

title: FOIA Request – Chicago 911 Call Data (Jan. 1, 2022 – Present) (Chicago Police Department)

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: FOIA Request – Chicago 911 Call Data (Jan. 1, 2022 – Present) (Chicago Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

Copies of Chicago’s 911 call records from January 1, 2022 through the most recent date available at the time this request is processed.

For each call, please include:
- The most detailed location information available (preferably exact address and GPS coordinates)
- Police district, ward, and beat/precinct
- Date and time of the call
- Priority level
- Call type/category/classification
- Whether the call was behavioral health–related
- Any additional metadata maintained for each call
- Any data dictionaries, codebooks, or similar documentation needed to interpret the records


If the records exist in a database or other structured format (e.g., geoJSON, CSV, Excel, GIS shapefile), please provide them in that format. If parts of the data are exempt from disclosure, release all non-exempt portions.

Clarifications: 
- If the data is stored in a CAD (Computer-Aided Dispatch) or RMS (Records Management System), please export all available fields, including field names, even if they are not part of regularly published reports.
- If any requested detail is not recorded for all calls, provide it where it exists.
- If there is an official dataset name for this information, providing that dataset is acceptable as long as it includes all requested fields.
- If the dataset is updated daily, please run the export on the date the request is fulfilled.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jenny Wadhwa

communications.subject: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. All email correspondence, with attachments, mentioning "Water Property Investors," "Water Property Investor II," or "Water Property Investor III." 

2. Pitch decks, prospectuses, or any other materials provided to NMERB by the the above funds for consideration of potential investments.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Julia Rock

communications.subject: Fw: [EXTERNAL] New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Records Requestor:


Your request for information from the New Mexico Educational Retirement Board was forwarded to me. In accordance with the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act (IPRA), “a written request shall provide the name, address and telephone number of the person seeking access to the records and shall identify the records sought with reasonable particularity.” Section 14-2-8(C) NMSA 1978.


If you will provide me with your name and mailing address, we can begin the process of allowing inspection of the relevant records.


The Inspection of Public Records Act can be found at 14-2-1 through 14-2-12 NMSA 1978.


Thank you.


Amanda Olsen



Amanda Olsen, Paralegal
NM Educational Retirement Board
PO Box 26129
Santa Fe, New Mexico 87502

(505) 827-8030 fax

Dear Mr. Scroggins and Ms. Olsen,

Thanks for the update. Can you provide any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request, or the estimated delivery date? Please feel free to give me a call at 781-962-8816 if it'd be helpful to discuss the scope of the materials we're requesting.

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock,

I am responding to your email yesterday requesting any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request. Please be assured that we make every effort to respond promptly to every request. However, we must also ensure that we are diligent and accurate in our reply. Thus, when obtained, all documents and emails must be reviewed. Additionally, we must rely on the state agency that controls the entire state email system to identify and provide the emails requested. As you can imagine, the process takes time.

As to an estimated response date, in our letter of August 1, 2023, we noted that we intend to respond by September 6, 2023.

Thank you for your patience and please feel free to contact me if you have further questions.

Respectfully,

[cid:image001.png@01D9C623.0D3F7D80]

communications.communication:
Hello Ms. Garcia,

Thank you for the update. Given that it's now been five months since we filed the initial request, are you able to provide an update as to whether you've identified the responsive documents, or what the source of the delay is?

Thank you,

Rebecca

communications.subject: ATTORNEY CLIENT PRIVILEGED - RE: [EXTERNAL] RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock and Ms. Burns,

Thank you for your inquiry and please accept our apologies for the delay.

As Mr. Scroggins noted in his August 3, 2023 email regarding our projected response, we always try to be prompt.  But as you might guess, the request references a large number of records.  As he said, we must thoroughly review all records to identify and obtain the responsive documents from both external and internal sources.  It is a complex and time-consuming process.

I am confident that we will have documents ready to provide on or before the December 6th, 2023, date noted in our recent communication.

Thank you for your continued patience!
Regards,
Renee



[cid:image002.png@01DA121F.C2136CB0]

Julia Rock

As discussed in our letter of December 6, 2023, we are providing the records we currently have available in response to your June 16, 2023, request.  They are located at the website below:

MuckRock - Julia Rock<https://nmgov-my.sharepoint.com/:f:/r/personal/renee_garcia_erb_nm_gov/Documents/MuckRock%20-%20Julia%20Rock?csf=1&web=1&e=4gwfSH>

As also discussed, we will require additional time to provide the remainder of the records.  We plan to provide additional documents on or before February 1, 2024.  Thank you again for your continued patience regarding this matter.
Regards,
Renee

title: Public Records Request — Courtney Clenney / Christian Obumseli Homicide (Miami-Dade State Attorney's Office)

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Public Records Request — Courtney Clenney / Christian Obumseli Homicide (Miami-Dade State Attorney's Office)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

Pursuant to Florida’s Public Records Law (Chapter 119, Florida Statutes), I request access to the following records relating to the homicide of Christian Obumseli by Courtney Clenney on April 3, 2022, at the One Paraiso Apartments, Miami, Florida:

- All body-worn camera footage from responding officers.
- Any dashcam or in-car camera recordings.
- All 911 call recordings associated with this incident.
- CAD dispatch logs and radio communications.
- Any interview room or interrogation recordings (audio/video) of Courtney Clenney or witnesses.
- Complete incident and investigative reports, including supplemental reports.
- Any crime scene evidence photos or videos generated in this case.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Richard Louis Trumka (1949 – 2021)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All records mentioning, concerning, or communicating with Richard Louis Trumka, deceased trade unionist and president of the AFL-CIO. 

Details which may assist in the location of records of relevance and elimination of duplicate names are below.

Full name: Richard Louis Trumka
Date of Birth: July 24, 1949
Date of Death:  August 5, 2021
First 5 digits of Social Security Number: 181-40

Trumka's death was widely reported in 2021 (see attachment); these records should thus be assumed to have diminished privacy interests from the FOIA Exemption 6, 7(C) as well as the Privacy Act. Records should be released in the public interest.

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the ELSUR Records System, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies.

If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that the Bureau has no other copies of said records.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

T. McElwee

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1502490-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on “Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request” on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI’s FOIPA Program is searching the FBI’s indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 152 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 922 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,964 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,360 days for processing.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FBI Records Management - Writ of Mandamus
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am seeking a thorough search of the Offices of David Hardy of the FBI Records Management Division for a copy of the cited ruling.  
2013-2020

And any related derivative documents related to the ruling. Including but not limited to internal memoranda in relation to adjustments to FOIA procedures.

'Case3:12-cv-03728-SI                       Document32                        Filed 07/01/13                            Page 1 of 18'

Courtesy copy attached 

EFOIA request.

Please produce in .pdf format pursuant to EFOIA Guidelines. 

Vaughn index requested for any items not produced in FOIA Response

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

William Fernandes

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] - RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #FOIA 1482790-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on "Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request" on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 104 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 853 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,786 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,500 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: Thank you for your recent contact
communications.communication:
Thank you for taking the time to contact the Judiciary Committee’s Republican Oversight and Investigations staff.

We will contact you if further information is needed to inquire into the issues you have raised.

Although we cannot pursue every allegation that we receive, that does not mean your concerns may not have merit.  You should consider reporting waste, fraud, abuse, or mismanagement elsewhere as well, if you have not already done so.  Confidential, protected whistleblower disclosures can also be made to:

•         the Office of Special Counsel (https://osc.gov/pages/file-complaint.aspx)
•         the Office of the Inspector General for the Department of Justice (http://www.justice.gov/oig/hotline/), or
•         the office of inspector general at another relevant agency (https://www.ignet.gov/contact-us).

If you report your concerns to one of these agencies, please let us know so that we can ensure that the agency treats it appropriately.  Should you have additional information to provide, please do not hesitate to forward it to us at this email address.  All disclosures are treated as protected, and none of the information will be used without consulting with you first.  Thank you.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Francis Boyd Moore (July 27, 1935 – May 22, 2025)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records mentioning, relating to, or generated as a result of investigation or inquiry into former Carter administration official Francis Boyd Moore (July 27, 1935 – May 22, 2025). His death is widely-known and widely reported; as such, privacy concerns under FOIA Exemptions 6 and 7 are voided, as are any concerns under the Privacy Act. For example, you may find his obituary in The New York Times at the following link: https://www.nytimes.com/2025/05/24/us/politics/frank-moore-dead.html

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records of both HQ and all field offices for all relevant names, agencies, organizations, companies and events including but not limited to those cited in the previous paragraphs and/or links as well as a cross-reference with the Southern Poverty Law Center to include any information provided by the SPLC. My request includes but is not limited to 137, 157, 176, 177, 183, 184, 188, and 214 files. If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

If any part of these documents are exempt from disclosure, please be sure to review and release all reasonably segregable nonexempt portions of responsive documents, as the FOIA requires.

I request that I be properly classified as a media requester. I am an assistant editor at Reason Magazine who has written numerous articles on topics of public interest, and I am requesting these documents in an editorial capacity. Please contact me if you have any questions about my media status.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Matthew Petti

Under the Virginia FOIA, I request:

1. Commonwealth of Virginia, Office of the Governor, Memorandum From: "Ralph S. Northam, Governor, VMI Class of 1981, Former President of VMI, Honor Court", "SUBJECT: Work Plan for Virginia Military Institute Equity Audit", Date October 30, 2020. Consists of at least 3 pages.

2. All records created or received between June 1, 2021 and the present concerning the removal, custody, transfer, or donation of Richmond’s Confederate monuments/statues, including transfers to BHMVA, The Valentine Museum, and the Swords Into Plowshares (SIP) project.

Please include:

Planning/Coordination – Drafts, emails, notes, and press coordination relating to the Dec. 30, 2021 joint plan with the City of Richmond regarding transfer to BHMVA and The Valentine.

DHR Involvement – Reviews, interpretations of Va. Code § 15.2-1812, and records concerning state custody/transfer of the Lee statue/pedestal.

Communications – All emails, texts, chats, and attachments with:

City of Richmond officials

The Valentine, BHMVA, JSAAHC/SIP

UVA (Barnes, Payton, Schmidt, Dubois, Dukes, Ochs)

Renée Grisham, Tom Perriello, Sally Hudson, Jennifer McClellan

All members of the VLBC, State Senator Ghazala Hashmi, and Rep. Abigail Spanberger (see Appendix for names)

Using search terms: “Swords Into Plowshares,” SIP, “Jefferson School,” “Valentine,” “BHMVA,” “Lee statue,” melt, destroy, recast.

Provide records in native electronic format. Please cite any exemptions.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tom Nash, a citizen of Virginia, in coordination with Anonymous.

communications.subject: RE: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: Virginia Monuments - Governor's Office
communications.communication:
Good morning:
            This office is in receipt of your request for records made in accordance with the Virginia Freedom of Information Act (§ 2.2-3700 et seq.). Please be advised that it is practically impossible to provide the requested records or determine whether they are available within the five work days required by FOIA because staff time required. Therefore, we are invoking subsection B 4 of § 2.2-3704 to provide us with an additional seven work days to respond to your request. All records matching your request will be sent to you electronically no later than COB Friday, September 5, 2025.
Thank you,
Stephanie Williams
FOIA Officer

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Police disciplinary files (Douglas County Prosecuting Attorney)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

- Any and all lists, spreadsheets or other organized datasets that detail potential or substantiated allegations of misconduct and/or impeached or impeachable testimony, created under Brady v. Maryland and/or Giglio v. United States.
- Any and all records regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations of internal department policy or criminal law by specific law enforcement officers.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Aspen Ford

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Officer K. McLaughlin Records
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any and all personnel records and files related to complaints, misconduct, and disciplinary actions involving officer Kevin McLaughlin of the Bellingham Police Department.

I am specifically requesting copies of the following documents:

Any formal complaints filed against officer McLaughlin either by members of the public, or by fellow officers or his superiors.

Any internal investigations conducted in response to these complaints or recorded misconduct, including all findings, communications, and conclusions.

Any disciplinary actions taken against officer McLaughlin as a result of these complaints or misconduct, including but not limited to suspension records, reprimands, and training records related to corrective actions.

Any records detailing the status, rank, and assignment of officer McLaughlin within the Bellingham Police Department.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Safe Community

communications.subject: Connecticut Freedom of Information Act Request: Connecticut Homicide Logs
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Connecticut Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of the State Police's Homicide logs, which should identify case numbers, detective names, weapon(s) used, location of homicide, motive and manner, and any other information the department has listed for homicides. I request such records for homicides that took place between Jan. 1, 2020 to present.

I also request that, if possible and pursuant to Conn. Gen. Stat. § 1-212(d), fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest and not made for commercial gain. The requested documents will be made available to the public at MuckRock.com.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 4 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Alexa Gagosz
